/i> ‘barley’ + <i>hlāw</i> ‘hill’; the latter probably has as its first element the derived adjective <i>beren</i> or the compound <i>bere-ærn</i> ‘barn’. There is also a place of this name in Derbyshire, named with Old English <i>bār</i> ‘boar’ or <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’, and one in Shropshire, which is from <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>lēah</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Barlowe","meanings":["English: variant of   Barlow  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Richard Barlow was born about 1237, in Chorlton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Henry Barlow, was 32 and his mother, Anne Shirwood, was 29. He married Matilda Townley about 1265, in Chorlton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1268, in Birley, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 32."},"et":{"ABT 1237–1268":"umbes 1237–1268","1237–1268":"1237–1268","1241–Female":"1241–Surnud","1268–Male":"1268–Surnud","1206–Male":"1206–Surnud","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1206":"1206","1237":"1237","1268":"1268","1210":"1210","1241":"1241","ABT 1237":"umbes 1237","about 1265":"umbes 1265","Barlow by Bury, Lancashire, England":"Barlow by Bury, Lancashire, England","Barlow, Chorlton, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Barley, Derbyshire, England":"Birley, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1237–1268":"noin 1237–1268","1237–1268":"1237–1268","1241–Female":"1241–Kuollut","1268–Male":"1268–Kuollut","1206–Male":"1206–Kuollut","1210–Female":"1210–Kuollut","1206":"1206","1237":"1237","1268":"1268","1210":"1210","1241":"1241","ABT 1237":"noin 1237","about 1265":"noin 1265","Barlow by Bury, Lancashire, England":"Barlow by Bury, Lancashire, England","Barlow, Chorlton, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Barley, Derbyshire, England":"Birley, Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"ABT 1237–1268":"environ 1237–1268","1237–1268":"1237–1268","1241–Female":"1241–Décédée","1268–Male":"1268–Décédé","1206–Male":"1206–Décédé","1210–Female":"1210–Décédée","1206":"1206","1237":"1237","1268":"1268","1210":"1210","1241":"1241","ABT 1237":"environ 1237","about 1265":"environ 1265","Barlow by Bury, Lancashire, England":"Barlow by Bury, Lancashire, Angleterre","Barlow, Chorlton, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Barley, Derbyshire, England":"Birley, De